<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870826-0123 </DOCNO><HL> Integrated Genetics Gets Patent</HL><DD> 08/26/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> INGN ANPHARMACEUTICALS, HOSPITAL SUPPLIES, MANAGEMENT (PHA) </IN><DATELINE> FRAMINGHAM, Mass.  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Integrated Genetics Inc. said it received a patent on its DNA probes for detecting salmonella bacteria.    The maker of diagnostic products said diagnostic kits using the patented technology currently are being marketed by GENE-TRAK Systems, a joint venture of Integrated Genetics and Amoco Corp., a Chicago-based energy concern. The patent covers the use of all DNA probes to detect salmonella in food products and in clinical samples, according to Integrated Genetics.    DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, is an essential component of all living matter and a basic material in the chromosomes of the cell nucleus; it contains the genetic code and transmits the hereditary pattern. </TEXT></DOC>